spossess aboriginal people, while the campaign to exterminate grasshoppers exposed class conflicts and competing versions of resettlement among immigrant ranchers.This unconventional history examines the lasting effects of range improvement, revealing a fascinating – and troubling – chapter of BC history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGrasshoppersxEcologyzBritish ColumbiaxHistory. 0aGrasshopperszBritish ColumbiaxHistory. 0aGrassland ecologyzBritish ColumbiaxHistory. 0aHuman ecologyzBritish ColumbiaxHistory. 0aRange ecologyzBritish ColumbiaxHistory. 0aWild horsesxEcologyzBritish ColumbiaxHistory. 0aWild horseszBritish ColumbiaxHistory. 7aNATURE / Animals / Horses.2bisacsh1 aWynn, Graeme, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2015z978311127402708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2015z978311127703508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2015z978311142000440uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077482839040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774828390423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774828390/original  a978-3-11-127402-7  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2015b2015  a978-3-11-127703-5  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2015b2015  a978-3-11-142000-4  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2015b2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles